A user opens a browser and enters www.foobar.com. The browser first asks a DNS server for the IP address associated with this domain name. The DNS server returns 8.8.8.8, which is the IP address of the server hosting the website.

A server is a physical machine or virtual machine that receives requests from other computers and provides services, files, or applications in response.

The domain name foobar.com is a human-readable name used to access the website instead of remembering its IP address. The www in www.foobar.com is an A record, which maps the hostname to the IPv4 address 8.8.8.8.

The user's browser communicates with the server using the HTTP or HTTPS protocol over the Internet.

Nginx acts as the web server. It receives HTTP requests from users, serves static files when needed, and forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

The application server runs the application logic. It processes requests, executes the application code, communicates with the database, and produces a response for Nginx to send back to the user.

The application files are the website's code base, such as backend code, configuration files, templates, and static assets.

MySQL is the database. It stores persistent data such as user accounts, passwords, posts, products, and other application information.

This infrastructure has several major problems:

Single Point of Failure: Everything runs on one server. If that server fails, the entire website becomes unavailable.
Downtime during maintenance: Restarting Nginx, the application server, or the whole machine for deployments or updates can make the website temporarily unavailable.
Limited scalability: One server has limited CPU, memory, disk, and network capacity. If traffic grows significantly, the server may become slow or crash.
